Single Org Results Summary

Nate Olson

June 3, 2016

Observations

  1. Overall high proportions of matches at species and genus level.
  2. The cumulative match proportions do not always reach 1.00, for example Staphylococcus genomes. This might be due to exclusion of unclassified and unknown matches from match level analysis or reads that bowtie (mapping algorithm) was unable to align to any sequece in the reference database.
  3. A number of unexpected genus, e.g. not Bacillus, Clostridium, Escherichia, Francisella, Listeria, Pseudonomas, Salmonella, Shigella, Staphylococcus, and Yersinia. These are strains that were either inadvertantly included in the study or reclassified genus.
  4. Some genus have high levels of family and higher matches. For Shigella most likely due to matches with Escherichia. Will need to verify. Good discussion point highlighting the importance of considering the taxa being evaluated and taxonomic ambiguities.

Match level by genus

Overall proportion of matches by taxonomic level. A number of strains from unexpected genus are present in the dataset. In general most matches are at the species or genus level. Species level matches include taxonomic ranks species group, species subgroup, subspecies, as well as species.

singleOrgMatchResults %>%
      mutate(lca_rank = ifelse(lca_rank %in% 
                                     c("species group", 
                                       "species subgroup", 
                                       "subspecies"), 
                               "species", lca_rank),
             lca_rank = factor(lca_rank, 
                               levels = c("species", "genus", 
                                          "family", "order", 
                                          "class","phylum",
                                          "superkingdom"))) %>% 
      group_by(Query, lca_rank) %>% 
      mutate(total_prop = sum(`Final Guess`)) %>% 
      ggplot() + geom_boxplot(aes(x = lca_rank, y = total_prop)) +
      geom_line(aes(x = lca_rank, y = total_prop, 
                               group = Query)) +
      facet_wrap(~query_genus, ncol = 4)  + 
      theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
      labs(x = "Taxonomic Level", y = "Match Proportion")
## geom_path: Each group consists of only one observation. Do you need to
## adjust the group aesthetic?

Classifications of unexpected genus

The unexpected genus are either reclassificed strains or were unintenially included in the study when grep was used to select genomes based on genus name. Only 23 of the strains are the unexpected genus out of 429 total strains evaluated in the study. As they are less than 5% of the total strains in the dataset, I am exluding them from the main analysis.

unexpected_genus_df <- singleOrgMatchResults %>%
      filter(!(query_genus %in% c("Bacillus", "Clostridium", "Escherichia", 
                                  "Francisella", "Listeria", "Pseudomonas", 
                                  "Salmonella", "Shigella", "Staphylococcus", 
                                  "Yersinia"))) %>% 
      select(query_taxid, query_genus) %>% distinct()
unexpected_class <- unexpected_genus_df$query_taxid %>% classification(db = 'ncbi')

      select(-id) %>% spread(rank, name) %>% 
      select(query, superkingdom, phylum, class, order, family, genus, species) %>%

Excluding unexpected genus

single_org_cum <- singleOrgMatchResults %>%
      filter(query_genus %in% c("Bacillus","Clostridium","Escherichia","Francisela","Listeria",
                                  "Pseudomonas","Salmonella","Shigella","Staphylococcus","Yersinia")) %>% 
      mutate(lca_rank = ifelse(lca_rank %in% 
                                     c("species group", 
                                       "species subgroup", 
                                       "subspecies"), 
                               "species", lca_rank)) %>% 
      group_by(Query, lca_rank, query_genus) %>% 
      summarise(total_prop = sum(`Final Guess`)) %>% 
      spread(lca_rank, total_prop,fill = 0)  %>% 
      gather(lca_rank, total_prop, -Query, -query_genus)  %>% 
     group_by(Query) %>% 
       mutate(lca_rank = factor(lca_rank, levels = c("species", "genus", 
                                    "family", "order", 
                                    "class","phylum",
                                    "superkingdom"))) %>%
      arrange(lca_rank) %>% 
      mutate(cum_prop = cumsum(total_prop))

Cumulative match by query

The cumulative match proportions are presented in three different ways below. It is interesting that the cumulative match proportions do not always reach 1.00. This is probably due to the proportion of reads that were not mapped, this would require justification if we include this point in the manuscript.

Faceted plots by genus

ggplot(single_org_cum) + 
            geom_path(aes(x = lca_rank, y = cum_prop, group = Query)) +
            facet_wrap(~query_genus) + 
            theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
            labs(x = "Taxonomic Level", y = "Cumulative Match Proportion")

Individual Plots by genus

plot_tax_cum <- function(df){
      p <- ggplot(df) + 
            geom_path(aes(x = lca_rank, y = cum_prop, group = Query)) +
            facet_wrap(~query_genus) + 
            theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
            labs(x = "Taxonomic Level", y = "Cumulative Proportion")
      print(p)
}
unique(single_org_cum$query_genus) %>% as.list() %>% set_names(.) %>% 
      map(~filter(single_org_cum, query_genus == .)) %>% walk(plot_tax_cum)

Boxplots by genus

Boxplots to compare distributions of cumulative match proportions by taxa for individual genus.

ggplot(single_org_cum) +
      geom_boxplot(aes(x = query_genus, y = cum_prop, color = query_genus), outlier.size = 0.5) +
      facet_wrap(~lca_rank, nrow = 1) + 
      theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), legend.position = "bottom") +
      labs(x = "Genus", color = "", y = "Cumulative Match Proportion")
